{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525223"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14068"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14068"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.16,0.2,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53631"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6727"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39091"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53631"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to a nephrologist for routine follow-up of her chronic kidney disease. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include metformin, glibenclamide, perindopril, hydrochlorothiazide, and lercanidipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR): 39 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin-to-creatinine ratio: 20 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["G3b A3","G4 A2","G3a A3","G3a A2","G3b A2"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s chronic kidney disease (CKD) stage is best described as \u003Cstrong\u003EG3b A2\u003C/strong\u003E. The staging of CKD is based on two factors: the estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) and the albuminuria grade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe eGFR of 38  mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E falls into the range of 30-44  mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, which corresponds to stage G3b. The \u0027G\u0027 in the staging refers to GFR category. The stages of CKD based on eGFR are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG1: \u226590 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG2: 60-89 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG3a: 45-59 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG3b: 30-44 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG4: 15-29 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EG5: \u0026lt;15 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2 \u003C/sup\u003E(or commenced dialysis)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe albuminuria grade is determined by the urinary albumin excretion. In this case, the ACR is 20 mg/mmol, which falls into the A2 category (moderately increased albuminuria). Based on the urinary albumin-creatinine ratio, the categories for albuminuria are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA1 (normal): \u0026lt;2.5 mg/mmol (male) and \u0026lt;3.5 mg/mmol (female)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA2 (moderately increased albuminuria): 2.5\u201325 mg/mmol (male) and 3.5\u201335 mg/mmol (female)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA3 (severely increased albuminuria): \u0026gt;25 mg/mmol (male) and \u0026gt;35 mg/mmol (female)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote the terms \u0027moderately increased albuminuria\u0027 and \u0027severely increased albuminuria\u0027 are preferable to the terms \u0027microalbuminuria\u0027 and \u0027macroalbuminuria\u0027 respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccurately classifying chronic kidney disease is essential to provide accurate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is staged based on eGFR and albuminuria grade.","The terms \u0027moderately increased albuminuria\u0027 and \u0027severely increased albuminuria\u0027 are preferable to the terms \u0027microalbuminuria\u0027 and \u0027macroalbuminuria\u0027 respectively."],"references":["Chapter 13: Chronic kidney disease prevention and management [Internet]. In: Racgp.org.au [online]. 2018. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/national-guide/chapter-13-chronic-kidney-disease-prevention-and-m"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39091"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14068"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"ty